<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,871,897]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rosa &amp; Aswathi &amp; Bijoy" authorityYear="2021" box="[554,619,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Chrysis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polita">
<emphasis box="[554,619,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">polita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(feminine, adjective) derives from Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[1192,1268,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">politus</emphasis>
, meaning both elegant (referred to the general habitus of this species), and polished (referred to punctation on the tergum II, with large and polished interspaces).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
